I have a theory
Stage One: Some lonely and depressed Anon finds /trash/, gets disgusted the fur and kink. Was once a person.
Stage Two: He sticks around, spending more & more time jerking off to unreal things. Doesn't give a fuck about original material.
Stage Three: He takes it too seriously, starts arguing. Soon he's barely wacking it but shitposting continually. Way too into gateway furry media like Starfox/Zootopia.
Stage Four: Starts reading the OP stories. Gets confused easily. Prefers greentext typed with one hand.
Stage Five: Has an idea bigger than his creative ability. Tries to write it, convinced his waifur is real.
Stage Six: Gives up again. Reads more, will argue for 10k words about species traits. Expert in what stories are good & which writefags are never good.
Stage Seven: Starts writing again. Develops a glimmer of hope. Works on being the better person his waifur would want.
Stage Eight: Not a great writefag, but capable. Has pity for those anons at stages three & lower, understands that stage four is the event horizon to a new life and won't shut the fuck up to anons at that level.
Stage Nine: A continuation of previous stage. Gets hated for his disingenuous, pedantic, & pretentious opinions. Waifur is for love and uspeakable taboos like ***********.
Stage Ten: A good enough writer that he's tried submitting to more traditional media. Hasn't made a penny from it. Depressed he's evolved beyond his old anon buddies, but silently visits once in a while. Might post once a month. Anons start remembering him fondly.
Stage Eleven: Struggles as a writer, but can call himself published. No longer depressed about how much time he spent on /trash/. Waifur is still a kind of muse, idealized but becoming more impersonal by the day.
Stage Twelve: Can support himself by his creativity. /trash/ is long forgotten, but the memories of his waifur remain. You can see it when you look in his eyes; she died years ago, a natural death after a long marriage.

>>34087371
Part of what you're going to struggle with is making the setting true to itself (not necessarily as the game describes it) without leaving ways for the reader to reason out of the literal hitler realm.
I've been there, and my way out was to give the readers peeks that said "You don't know everything"
By the time some the lessons hit home, instead of a black&white moralism you have no real heroes. The reader can side with one based on their pre-held opinions, but risk falling down their own slippery slope arguments.

It amuses me. Too many readers these days fall into the LBGT trap of "But what would this mean in our world?" Surface allegory is how you beat the puppy, aka reader, into divorcing themselves from the here & now.
But what do I know? Many writers do it so poorly there's nothing beneath the surface allegory to pivot to. In a year those real world situations have changed, and the power of the example lost.
Like >>34087399 said, even mostly utter bastards have a different side. Finding out what's worse, that's fun.
